Dear Mr Miller,

I am writing to express my profound disappointment and anger at the state of healthcare in our constituency, a situation that has escalated to an intolerable level over the past few months. The local NHS Trust has been in a state of disarray, and the lack of action from your office is nothing short of a dereliction of duty.

The Eastfield Community Hospital, which once served as a beacon of hope for our elderly, now operates with a skeletal staff. I have witnessed the same GP surgery on Main Street, where patients are turned away because the clinic has run out of appointment slots for over a year. Mrs. Patel, a 78‑year‑old resident, was denied a routine check‑up last week, forcing her to travel to the city hospital, a 45‑minute drive, to receive basic care that should have been available locally. Dear Mr Miller,

I am writing to thank you for your recent support of the neighbourhood policing partnership in our ward and to share a few thoughts on how we can further reduce crime and build confidence in local safety.

Over the past year I have seen a noticeable rise in shop‑lifting incidents on the high street, especially in the early evenings. A small family shop on St. James Street was forced to close for a week after a burglary that left the owner with a broken arm. The shopkeeper, Mrs Harris, is a long‑time resident and has been a pillar of our community for over 30 years. She has asked for more visible patrols and better CCTV coverage. I know that the police have already increased foot patrols during peak times, but a dedicated “shop‑keeper liaison” role could help coordinate support and share best practice.

Dear Mr Miller,

I am writing to express my deep concern about the recent changes to the pension system that are affecting so many of our older residents. As a long‑time resident of the constituency, I have seen the impact of these cuts on my neighbour, Mrs. Patel, who has been receiving a reduced state pension for the past year. She now struggles to afford her monthly medication and the heating in her small flat, which has become a constant source of worry for her family.

The local council’s budget is already stretched thin, and the reduction in pension benefits is forcing more people to rely on the limited support services we have. I have spoken with several pensioners who are now unable to attend the weekly community centre sessions that help them stay socially active. These sessions are crucial for preventing isolation, yet the financial strain has made attendance impossible for many.

Dear Mr Miller,

I am writing to express my profound disappointment and anger at the way you have handled the immigration crisis in our constituency. Your recent statements in Parliament, claiming that “immigration is a national issue that must be managed fairly,” are a thin veil over the reality that our streets, schools, and local economy are being strangled by a policy that has no regard for the well‑being of ordinary Britons.

Dear Mr Miller,

I am writing to express my profound disappointment with the way you have handled the housing crisis in our constituency. As a long‑standing resident of the East End of Luton, I have witnessed the council’s failure to deliver on its promises, and your silence on these matters is unacceptable.

The council’s housing stock is in a state of disrepair. I have personally seen the roof of the 1970s block on Houghton Road leak during the last storm, yet the maintenance team has not been scheduled for a fix for over a year. Tenants are left to endure damp, mould and the constant threat of structural failure. Your office has repeatedly assured us that “improvements are underway,” but no concrete action has followed. The lack of a transparent timetable for repairs is a blatant disregard for the safety and wellbeing of your constituents.

Dear Mr Miller,

I write to you from the heart of the East End of Birmingham, where the streets of Aston and Sparkbrook have become a living nightmare for ordinary residents. Over the past year, the crime rate in our ward has risen by a staggering 18 %, and the impact on families is palpable. I am compelled to bring this to your attention because the safety of our community is slipping through the cracks of policy and neglect.

The first incident that rattled our neighbourhood was the break‑in at the local primary school on a quiet Tuesday. A group of teenagers forced their way into the staff room, stealing laptops and a stack of lesson plans. The school’s security system, which was installed a decade ago, was bypassed with a simple lock‑pick. The incident left teachers feeling vulnerable and parents anxious about their children’s safety. Dear Mr Miller,

I am writing to express my profound disappointment and frustration with the current state of taxation policy, which is having a devastating impact on every resident of our constituency. The recent hikes in council tax, the relentless increase in income tax, and the lack of any meaningful relief for the middle‑class families who are already stretched to the limit are simply unacceptable.

Our local council has raised the council tax by 8% this year, a figure that is far beyond the 3% increase that was promised in the last budget review. For a family like mine, with two children and a single income, this means an extra £250 a year that we cannot afford. We are already paying more than the national average for utilities, and the cost of living crisis is only getting worse. Dear Mr Miller,

I am writing to express my deep frustration with the current immigration policy and its impact on our constituency. Over the past year, the influx of migrants has overwhelmed our local services, and I have seen the strain firsthand. At the community centre in Westfield, the waiting list for language classes has stretched to three months, and the staff are barely keeping up. The local primary school, St. Mary's, is now over capacity; teachers are forced to split classes, and the quality of education is slipping. Dear Mr Miller,

I am writing to express my profound disappointment with the way you have handled the housing crisis in our constituency. The council’s latest housing plan is a mockery of any real attempt to address the acute shortage of affordable homes. Since the council’s announcement last year, the number of people on the waiting list has surged by over 30 %, yet you have repeatedly failed to secure any additional funding from Westminster.

The new “green‑field” scheme you promoted in the last constituency meeting is nothing more than a convenient excuse to build luxury apartments on the edge of the town, while the very real need for social housing remains unmet. I have seen families, including my neighbour’s two‑year‑old, living in overcrowded, sub‑standard flats that are in disrepair. The council’s maintenance budget is a joke – the windows in the old council block at 12 Oak Street are still broken, and the landlord has ignored the repeated complaints.

Your recent statement that “the market will correct itself” is not only naïve but dangerous. The local market is already saturated with speculative developments that cater to investors, not residents. The lack of a robust, enforceable plan for new affordable units is a direct failure of your office

Dear Mr Miller,

I am writing to express my deep concern about the state of education in our constituency, particularly the situation at St. Andrew’s Primary School in Eastfield and the secondary schools in the surrounding villages. Over the past few years, the quality of education has deteriorated to a point where parents, students and teachers are left feeling abandoned by the system that is supposed to support them.

Dear Mr Miller,

I am writing to you as a resident of the North West ward and a long‑time pensioner who has seen the changes in our local pension landscape over the past decade. I would like to thank you for your continued support of the pension rights of our community, and to share some observations and suggestions that I believe could help strengthen the security and dignity of those of us who rely on our pensions to live comfortably.

Over the last few years, I have watched the cost of living in our town rise steadily, with food, heating and transport costs climbing faster than the pension increases that many of us receive. I have spoken to several neighbours in the St. Mary's Estate who are struggling to keep up with the rising energy bills, and I have seen the impact of the recent cuts to the local council’s pensioner discount scheme on their ability to afford public transport.

Dear Mr Miller,

I am writing from the heart of the East End, where the streets that once felt safe now echo with the sound of sirens and the uneasy silence of residents who fear stepping outside after dark. Over the past year, the number of break‑ins, vehicle thefts and anti‑social behaviour in our neighbourhood has risen sharply. Last week a shop on High Street was robbed at gunpoint, and the owner, Mrs. Patel, was left shaken and unable to rest. The local police station, which is already stretched thin, has struggled to respond promptly to the surge in incidents.

I am concerned that the current policing strategy, which prioritises high‑profile areas, is leaving communities like ours vulnerable. The lack of visible patrols on the corner of St. Mary's Road and 12th Avenue has emboldened offenders. Residents have started to rely on private security, which is unaffordable for many. Dear Mr Miller,

I am writing to bring to your attention several environmental concerns that have become increasingly apparent in our constituency. Dear Mr Miller,

I am writing to thank you for your recent work on the environmental policy review and to share some local observations that I hope will help shape future initiatives in our constituency.

Living in the outskirts of the town, I have seen the transformation of the old industrial site on Oak Lane into a vibrant community garden. The project not only reclaimed a derelict space but also created a haven for pollinators and a source of fresh produce for residents. I would love to see more of these green‑roof and community‑garden schemes replicated across the borough, especially on the vacant plots behind the old mill and the disused railway line that runs through the valley.
